==English==

===Etymology===
From {{S.}} ''[[embargar]]'' 'to arrest' and {{E.}} ''[[barge]]'' 'to force'.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|embarges|embarging|embarged|embarged}}

# {{transitive}} To impose oneself upon another, often against their will.
# {{transitive}} To forcefully share an unwanted opinion.
#*He had unknowingly '''embarged''' himself upon her, and only wanted to be loved in return.

